ted%20to%20winning%20rights%20for%20the%20black%20majority%20in%20white-ruled%20South%20Africa%20and%20Mandela%20was%20made%20the%20Deputy%20National%20President%20of%20the%20organization%20in%201952.%5Cn%5CnHis%20forms%20of%20protests?%20Nonviolent%20strikes,%20boycotts,%20marches%20and%20other%20civil%20disobedience%20acts.%20%5CnRight%20after%20the%20massacre%20of%20peaceful%20black%20demonstrators%20at%20Sharpeville,%201960,%20Mandela%20organized%20a%20paramilitary%20branch%20of%20the%20ANC%20to%20engage%20in%20acts%20of%20sabotage%20against%20the%20white%20minority%20government;%20consequently,%20he%20was%20arrested%20and%20sentenced%20to%20five%20years%20in%20Robben%20Island%20Prison,%20and%20was%20later%20in%201964,%20sentenced%20to%20life%20imprisonment.%5CnHis%20prison%20time%20was%20rough%20and%20brutal%20and%20all%20forms%20of%20communications%20were%20terminated%20with%20the%20outside%20world.%20However,%20his%20resolve%20remained%20unabashed%20and%20he%20became%20a%20symbol%20for%20the%20anti-apartheid%20movement%20which%20started%20growing%20rampantly.%20In%201982,%20he%20was%20moved%20to%20Pollsmoor%20Prison,%20and%20later%20in%201988,%20he%20was%20put%20under%20house%20arrest%20in%20a%20cottage%20on%20the%20mainland.%5CnNelson%20was%20released%20on%2011th%20of%20February,%201990%20on%20the%20orders%20of%20F.W.%20de%20Klerk,%20the%20then%20South%20African%20President,%20lifted%20the%20ban%20on%20ANC.%20Klerk%20and%20Mandela%20subsequently%20led%20the%20ANC%20in%20its%20negotiations%20with%20the%20minority%20government%20for%20an%20end%20to%20apartheid%20and%20the%20establishment%20of%20a%20multiracial%20government,%20and%20consequently,%20they%20jointly%20won%20the%20Nobel%20Peace%20Prize%20of%201993.%20%5CnOn%20the%20April%20of%201994,%20the%20ANC%20won%20after%20more%20than%2022%20million%20South%20Africans%20cast%20their%20vote%20in%20the%20country%E2%80%99s%20first%20free%20multiracial%20parliamentary%20election,%20and%20exactly%2024%20years%20fro