(484, 1, '2018-05-27 20:50:06', '2018-05-27 15:20:06', 'The time for the healing of the wounds has come - Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela.\r\n\r\nThe African National Congress (ANC) was a black political organization dedicated to winning rights for the black majority in white-ruled South Africa and Mandela was made the Deputy National President of the organization in 1952.\r\n\r\nHis forms of protests? Nonviolent strikes, boycotts, marches and other civil disobedience acts.\r\n<div class=\"text_exposed_show\">\r\n\r\nRight after the massacre of peaceful black demonstrators at Sharpeville, 1960, Mandela organized a paramilitary branch of the ANC to engage in acts of sabotage against the white minority government; consequently, he was arrested and sentenced to five years in Robben Island Prison, and was later in 1964, sentenced to life imprisonment.\r\nHis prison time was rough and brutal and all forms of communications were terminated with the outside world. However, his resolve remained unabashed and he became a symbol for the anti-apartheid movement which started growing rampantly. In 1982, he was moved to Pollsmoor Prison, and later in 1988, he was put under house arrest in a cottage on the mainland.\r\nNelson was released on 11th of February, 1990 on the orders of F.W. de Klerk, the then South African President, lifted the ban on ANC. Klerk and Mandela subsequently led the ANC in its negotiations with the minority government for an end to apartheid and the establishment of a multiracial government, and consequently, they jointly won the Nobel Peace Prize of 1993.\r\n\r\nOn the April of 1994, the ANC won after more than 22 million South Africans cast their vote in the countrys first free multiracial parliamentary election, and exactly 24 years from today, Mandela was inaugurated as the first black President of South Africa, on the 10th of May, 1994.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '482-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-05-27